{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20161229142435|757223947","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Seth_Moulton","to":"Seth Moulton"}],"pages":{"43714153":{"pageid":43714153,"ns":0,"title":"Seth Moulton","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2016-12-30T21:33:16Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox politician\n| image         = Seth Moulton.jpg\n| caption       =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1978|10|24}}\n| birth_place   = [[Salem, Massachusetts]]\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| state         = [[Massachusetts]]\n| district      = {{ushr|MA|6|6th}}\n| term_start    = January 3, 2015\n| term_end      =\n| preceding    = [[John F. Tierney]]\n| party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| spouse        =\n| religion      = [[Christianity|Christian]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Religions of our representatives|publisher=The Washington Post|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/114th-house-religions/|accessdate=February 6, 2015}}</ref>\n| residence     = [[Salem, Massachusetts]]\n| occupation    = [[Military officer]], [[businessman]]\n| education      = [[Phillips Academy Andover|Phillips Academy]], [[Andover, Massachusetts|Andover]], [[Massachusetts]]\n| alma_mater    = [[Harvard University]] <small>([[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]], [[Master of Business Administration|M.B.A.]], [[Master of Public Administration|M.P.A.]])</small>\n| allegiance    = {{nowrap|{{flag|United States of America}}}}\n| branch        = [[File:Flag of the United States Marine Corps.svg|border|20px]] [[United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps]]\n| serviceyears  = 2001\u20132008\n| rank          = [[File:US-O3 insignia.svg|15px]] [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]]\n| battles       = [[Iraq War]]\n| mawards       = [[File:Bronze Star ribbon.svg|20px|border]] [[Bronze Star Medal]]<br />[[File:Navy and Marine Corps Commendation ribbon.svg|20px]] [[Commendation Medal]]\n| website       = {{URL|https://moulton.house.gov/|U.S. House website}}\n}}\n'''Seth Wilbur Moulton''' (born October 24, 1978) is an American former [[United States Marine Corps|Marine Corps]] [[Military Officer|officer]] and a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] member of the [[United States House of Representatives]], representing [[Massachusetts's 6th congressional district]].\n\nAfter graduating from [[Harvard University]] in 2001 with a [[Bachelor of Science]] in [[physics]], Moulton joined the [[United States Marine Corps]]. He served four tours in the [[Iraq War]] and between those tours earned his [[master's degree]]s in [[Master of Business Administration|business]] and [[Master of Public Administration|public administration]] in a [[Double degree|dual program]] at Harvard University.\n\nHe entered politics in 2014, running for Massachusetts's 6th congressional district. He defeated incumbent Congressman [[John F. Tierney]] in the Democratic primary and then defeated former Republican State Senator [[Richard Tisei]] in the general election.\n\n==Early life, education, and commission==\nSeth Wilbur Moulton was born on October 24, 1978, in [[Salem, Massachusetts]], the son of Lynn Alice (n\u00e9e Meader), a secretary, and Wilbur Thomas Moulton, Jr., a real estate attorney.<ref name=madepeace/><ref>{{cite web|title=0695. Lynn Alice Meade|url=http://www.themeaderfamily.org/test/showPage.php?ID=0695 |publisher=Meader Family Organization|accessdate=November 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Gomes|first1=Peter J. |title=The Good Life: Truths That Last in Times of Need|date=2003|publisher=HarperOne|page=365|url=http://librarum.org/book/24442/365|accessdate=November 6, 2014}}</ref> Moulton grew up in [[Marblehead, Massachusetts]], as the oldest of three siblings.<ref name=madepeace>{{cite news|url=http://www.bostonmagazine.com/2008/01/how-the-moultons-made-peace-with-the-war|title=How the Moultons Made Peace with the War|work=[[Boston Magazine]]|author=Phyllis Karas|date=February 2008}}</ref> He graduated from [[Phillips Academy Andover]], a co-educational boarding and day [[university-preparatory school]] in [[Andover, Massachusetts|Andover]], [[Massachusetts]] in 1997,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andover.edu/calendar/pages/moultontalk2014.aspx|work=[[Phillips Academy]]|title=Seth Moulton '97 talks about service on April 22}}</ref> and attended [[Harvard University]], where he earned his [[Bachelor of Science]] in [[physics]] in 2001. He gave the Undergraduate English Oration at his [[commencement address]], focusing on the importance of service.<ref name=warprofiles>{{cite news|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2003/6/5/war-profiles-seth-w-moulton-01|title=War Profiles: Seth W. Moulton '01, 2nd Lieutenant, U.S. Marine Corps|work=[[Harvard Crimson]]|date=June 5, 2003}}</ref> \n\nMoulton joined the Marine Corps after graduation, a few months before the [[September 11 attacks]],<ref name=disillusioned>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/09/us/politics/disillusioned-in-iraq-but-prodded-to-serve-again.html|title=Disillusioned in Iraq, but Prodded to Serve Again|work=[[New York Times]]|author=Jeremy W. Peters|date=February 8, 2015}}</ref> and attended the [[Officer Candidate School]] in [[Quantico, Virginia]]. After graduating in 2002 with the rank of [[second lieutenant]], Moulton was among the first service members to enter [[Baghdad]] at the beginning of the [[Iraq War]].<ref name=madepeace/><ref name=warprofiles/>\n\n==Military career==\nDuring the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], Moulton led one of the first infantry platoons to enter [[Baghdad]]. He served a total of four tours of duty in [[Iraq]] from 2003 to 2008.<ref name=madepeace/> Moulton took part in the 2003 [[Battle of Nasiriyah]], leading a platoon that cleared a hostile stronghold. In that action, he went to the aid of a Marine wounded by friendly fire, and for his actions he was awarded the [[Commendation Medal|Navy and Marine Corps Commendation Medal]] for valor.<ref name=underplays>{{cite news|url=http://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2014/10/17/moulton-underplays-military-service/lY9FfmOrviwL2LAFHr61dO/story.html|title=Seth Moulton underplays military service|first=Walter V. |last=Robinson |date=October 18, 2014|work=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref> Moulton was active in combat against insurgent forces in Iraq, including the 2004 [[Battle of Najaf (2004)|Battle of Najaf]] against the militia of [[Muqtada al-Sadr]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pbs.org/now/shows/316/No-End-in-Sight.html|work=[[PBS]]|date=April 20, 2007|title=Director's Interview: Charles Ferguson}}</ref> Over two days, he \"fearlessly exposed himself to enemy fire\" as his platoon was pinned down under heavy fire and then directed the supporting fire that repelled the attack. He received the [[Bronze Star Medal]] for his actions in this battle.<ref name=underplays/>\n\nHe told only his campaign manager, a former Marine, about these awards, keeping them secret even from his parents. When ''[[Boston Globe]]'' reporter [[Walter V. Robinson]] disclosed in October 2014 that Moulton had earned the Bronze Star and the Commendation Medal, Moulton said that \"There is a healthy disrespect among veterans who served on the front lines for people who walk around telling war stories\". He said he was uncomfortable calling attention to his own awards out of respect to \"many others who did heroic things and received no awards at all.\" He asked Robinson not to refer to him as a hero: \"Look, we served our country, and we served the guys next to us. And it's not something to brag about.\" The ''Globe'' reported that \"his voice choked with emotion\" as he added: \"The greatest honor of my life was to lead these men in my platoon, even though it was a war that I and they disagreed with.\"<ref name=underplays/>\n\nIn 2008, General [[David Petraeus]] requested Moulton's assignment to work as a special liaison with tribal leaders in Southern Iraq during his fourth tour of duty in Iraq. Following that tour, Moulton left the Marine Corps with the rank of captain.<ref name=madepeace/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.phillipian.net/articles/2014/09/11/seth-moulton-97-wins-democratic-party-primary|title=Seth Moulton '97 Wins The Democratic Party Primary|first=Kailash|last=Sundaram|date=September 12, 2014|work=[[Phillips Academy]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2014/05/11/marine-veteran-seth-moulton-wages-insurgent-campaign-against-fellow-democrat-john-tierney/3RdZyq5hE0o8QicDcNGVQO/story.html|title=Marine Veteran Seth Moulton Wages Insurgent Campaign Against Fellow Democrat John Tierney|work=[[Boston Globe]]|date=May 11, 2014|first=Stephanie|last=Ebbert|accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Media contributions===\nIn 2003, Moulton co-hosted a television program with his Iraqi interpreter, Mohammed Harba, called \"Moulton and Mohammed,\" during which they discussed regional conditions in the period following the U.S. invasion before an audience of U.S. servicemen and Iraqi citizens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weekendamerica.publicradio.org/programs/2007/01/06/moulton_amp_mohammed.html |title=Moulton & Mohammed|work=[[American Public Media]]|date=January 6, 2007}}</ref> The show ended after three months when Moulton's unit left the area.<ref name=madepeace/>\n\nBetween 2003 and 2008, Moulton was frequently interviewed about his experiences as an officer in Iraq by U.S. national media, including [[CNN]], [[MSNBC]], and [[National Public Radio|NPR]] programs ''[[Morning Edition]]'' and ''[[All Things Considered]]''.<ref name=madepeace/><ref name=\"NPR interviews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.npr.org/templates/search/index.php?searchinput=seth+moulton|title=Search Results:Seth Moulton}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = And are you telling me that's the best America can do? No. Don't tell me that, don't tell the Marines who fought for a month in [[Najaf]] that, don't tell the marines who are still fighting every day in [[Fallujah]] that that's the best America can do... That makes me angry.|source=[[No End in Sight]], ''Seth Moulton''|width=50%|align=right}}\n\nMoulton was also prominently featured in the [[Academy Award]]-nominated 2007 documentary ''[[No End in Sight]]''. In the film, Moulton criticized the U.S. government's handling of the [[History of Iraq (2003\u201311)|occupation of Iraq]]. [[UCLA]] anthropology professor [[Sherry Ortner]] wrote that Moulton's comments \"sum[med] up the emotional tone of the film.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ortner|first1=Sherry B.|title=Not Hollywood: Independent Film at the Twilight of the American Dream|date=2013|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=978-0822354260|page=245|url=https://books.google.com/?id=aIqdEw2VToUC&pg=PA245|accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his return from active duty with the Marines in 2008, Moulton attended a dual degree program at the [[Harvard Business School]] and the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government|Harvard Kennedy School]], receiving [[master's degree]]s in [[Master of Business Administration|business]] and [[public administration]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Sullivan Jim|title=Tierney faces Democratic challenger for his seat|url=http://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2013/07/06/representative-john-tierney-facing-primary-challenge-from-within-his-own-democratic-party-byfellow-democrat-marine-seth-moulton/MezmoWMuXBlnh28g3zIPxL/story.html|accessdate=September 13, 2014|work=Boston Globe|date=July 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Private sector career==\nAfter graduate school, Moulton worked for one year as managing director of the [[Texas Central Railway]], a transportation firm which is in the process of building a [[high-speed rail]] connection between [[Houston, Texas|Houston]] and [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth]], [[Texas]].<ref name=globeedit>{{cite news|url=http://www.bostonglobe.com/opinion/editorials/2014/09/01/democratic-primary-endorsement-seth-moulton-for-congress/LAmkYNWsDafuuleivth96L/story.html|title=Seth Moulton For Congress|work=[[Boston Globe]]|date=September 2, 2014|accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n\n====2012 speculation====\nMoulton had considered running against Democratic Representative [[John F. Tierney]] of [[Massachusetts's 6th congressional district]] as an Independent in the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Massachusetts, 2012#District 6|2012 elections]], but he decided against it in July 2012, saying that \"the time and the logistics of putting together all the campaign infrastructure, organizing the volunteers ... the fundraising\u2014it's just too much to accomplish in three months.\" Had he run and been elected, he would have caucused with the Democrats. He told ''Roll Call'' that his own polling \"showed there was in fact a clear path to victory\" and said he might run for office in the future.<ref>{{cite news|title=Massachusetts: Independent Seth Moulton Will Not Run|url=http://atr.rollcall.com/massachusetts-independent-seth-moulton-will-not-run |accessdate=October 8, 2014|work=Roll Call|date=July 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2014 election====\nOn July 8, 2013, Moulton announced his candidacy in the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Massachusetts, 2014#District 6|2014 congressional race]] for [[Massachusetts's 6th congressional district|Massachusetts' 6th district]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Moulton Launches Tierney Challenge|url=http://www.lowellsun.com/news/ci_23632217/moulton-launches-tierney-challenge|first=Katie|last=Lannan|accessdate=October 25, 2014|work=Lowell Sun|date=July 10, 2013}}</ref> The race had been recognized for its competitiveness by national and regional media throughout the election cycle.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.com/the-daily-rundown/the-39-democrats-who-broke-ranks-obama |title=The 39 Democrats who broke ranks from Obama|publisher=[[MSNBC]]|date= November 15, 2013|accessdate=November 11, 2014|first=Jessica|last=Taylor}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/01/01/politics/2014-house-races/index.html |title=5 House Races to Watch in 2014| publisher= [[CNN]] |date= January 1, 2014|accessdate=November 11, 2014|first1=Leigh Ann|last1= Caldwell |first2= Paul|last2= Steinhauser}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.rollcall.com/rothenblog/top-5-races-to-watch-in-new-england-2/?dcz= |title=Top 5 Races to Watch in New England| first=Nathan L.|last=Gonzales |work=[[Roll Call]]|date= August 21, 2014|accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref><ref name=battle>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3204263/a-battle-of-two-veterans/ |title=A Battle of Two Veterans |first=Joe |last=Klein |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date= August 28, 2014|accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://washingtonexaminer.com/iraq-vet-gives-tierney-tough-challenge-in-massachusetts/article/2552774 |title=Iraq vet gives Tierney tough challenge in Massachusetts| work=Washington Examiner |date=September 3, 2014|accessdate=November 11, 2014|first=Betsy|last=Woodruff}}</ref> Moulton challenged incumbent Congressman John Tierney in the Democratic [[primary election|primary]]. According to ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine political columnist [[Joe Klein]], Moulton \"has refused to distinguish himself from Tierney on most issues. He's running on freshness and dynamism.\"<ref name=battle/> The ''Boston Globe'' editorial board wrote: \"Moulton and Tierney share nearly identical political views, but Moulton's background, and his approach to discussing the issues, suggests an openness to new perspectives.\"<ref name=globeedit/>\n\nTierney's campaign claimed in campaign advertisements that Moulton received campaign contributions from a [[New Hampshire]] [[political action committee]] that previously donated only to [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]], implying that Moulton must hold conservative views.<ref name=attack>{{cite news|url=http://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2014/09/02/john-tierney-launches-attack-against-democratic-challenger/TY8shjpb0yq4sIvu00S1DN/story.html |title=John Tierney Launches Attack Against Democratic Challenger|work= Boston Globe |date= September 2, 2014|accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref> Moulton denied being more conservative than his opponent,<ref name=Iraqvote>{{cite news|url=http://www.bostonglobe.com/opinion/2014/08/17/seth-moulton-puts-john-tierney-iraq-vote-back-play/E9o1a9BVuihUzgkggu0zKO/story.html |title=Seth Moulton puts John Tierney\u2019s Iraq vote back in play |work=Boston Globe |date= August 8, 2014|accessdate=November 11, 2014}}</ref> and stated that the Republican PAC donation was returned. Public [[Federal Election Commission]] filings confirmed that the donation was returned in February 2014.<ref name=attack/>\n\nMoulton said that he personally opposed the Iraq War in which he served. A Tierney campaign staff member said that Moulton had \"changed his mind\" and highlighted Tierney's vote in Congress to oppose [[Iraq Resolution|the 2002 resolution authorizing the U.S. Invasion of Iraq]].<ref name=Iraqvote/> Moulton also received the first-ever political endorsement from [[Stanley McChrystal|Ret. Gen. Stanley McChrystal]] during the campaign.<ref>[http://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2014/08/04/former-gen-stanley-mcchrystal-endorse-congressional-hopeful-seth-moulton/fRb3G9dh9Soue7CWfOSKpJ/story.html \"Retired Gen. McChrystal endorses congress hopeful Moulton\" by Joshua Miller, ''Boston Globe'', August 4, 2014]</ref>\n\nMoulton defeated Tierney in the primary, winning with 50.8% of the vote to Tierney's 40.1%.<ref>{{cite web|title=Massachusetts Election Statistics |url=http://electionstats.state.ma.us/elections/search/year_from:2014/year_to:2014/stage:Primaries|website=Massachusetts Election Division|accessdate=October 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nMoulton was endorsed by Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Elizabeth Warren endorses Seth Moulton for Congress|url=http://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2014/09/27/sen-warren-endorses-moulton-for-congress/WWJckEXXGYU8PyFTSCaqiJ/story.html|accessdate=October 14, 2014|agency=Associated Press| work=Boston Globe|date=September 28, 2014}}</ref> for the general election. In October 2014, he withdrew from a debate sponsored by radio station [[WGBH (FM)|WGBH]] because of a series of New York fundraisers, where he welcomed Democratic National Committee Chairwoman [[Debbie Wasserman Schultz]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stout |first1=Matt|title=Richard Tisei rips Seth Moulton cash grab in 6th|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news_opinion/local_politics/2014/10/richard_tisei_rips_seth_moulton_cash_grab_in_6th|accessdate=October 14, 2014|work=Boston Herald|date=October 7, 2014}}</ref> The Moulton and Tisei campaigns were held up as an example of how candidates can compete with respect for each other.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Zengerle|first1=Jason|title=This Massachusetts Race Will Restore Your Faith in Our Democracy |url=http://www.newrepublic.com/article/120109/tisei-moulton-race-mass-rare-choice-two-great-candidates |accessdate=November 5, 2014|work=New Republic|date=November 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nMoulton defeated Republican nominee [[Richard Tisei]] in the general election.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\n====2016 election====\nMoulton was uncontested for re-election in 2016.<ref>http://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/massachusetts-house-district-6</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nMoulton was sworn in to the [[114th United States Congress]] on January 3, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://moulton.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/representative-sworn-into-office|title=Congressman Seth Moulton Sworn-in to 114th Congress|accessdate=January 6, 2015}}</ref>\n{{U.S. Congress committee assignments\n |congress=114\n |ref=<ref>{{cite web|url=https://moulton.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/congressman-moulton-named-house-budget-committee|title=CONGRESSMAN MOULTON NAMED TO HOUSE BUDGET COMMITTEE|accessdate=January 21, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://moulton.house.gov/media-center/press-releases/congressman-seth-moulton-named-house-armed-services-committee|title=CONGRESSMAN MOULTON NAMED TO HOUSE ARMED SERVICES COMMITTEE|accessdate=January 9, 2015}}</ref>\n |committees=\n* '''[[United States House Committee on the Budget|Budget]]'''\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Armed Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces|Tactical Air and Land Forces]]\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces|Seapower and Projection Forces]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Small Business|Small Business]]'''\n** [[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Health and Technology|Health and Technology]] (Ranking Member)\n}}\nMoulton is one of five House members who has been \"far more reliant on the financial world\" to finance his 2016 election campaigns than most others running for a [House] seat, raising $255,799 from the securities and investment industry, with Goldman Sachs and Warren Buffett\u2019s Berkshire Hathaway standing out.<ref name=\"crp\">{{cite web | url=http://www.opensecrets.org/news/2016/06/wall-streets-fab-five-the-house-candidates-most-dependent-on-the-finance-industry/ | title=Wall Street\u2019s fab five: House members, candidates most reliant on funding from finance industry | publisher=Center for Responsive Politics | date=1 June 2016 | accessdate=8 June 2016 | author=Will Tucker}}</ref>\n\n===Political views===\nIn Moulton's campaign advertisements, he has referred to himself as a  \"progressive Democrat\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Seth Moulton said he smoked Pot at Harvard, supports legalization|url=http://www.nobomagazine.com/2014/08/13/congressional-candidate-seth-moulton-releases-first-tv-advertisement|accessdate=6 April 2016|publisher=NoBo Magazine|date=August 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nMoulton is a member of the [[New Democrat Coalition]], which is a [[congressional caucus]] made up of Democrats who support an agenda that the organization describes as \"pro-growth and fiscally-responsible.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Membership|url=https://newdemocratcoalition-kind.house.gov/membership |accessdate=March 22, 2016|publisher=New Democrat Coalition|date=March 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Views on marijuana====\nSeth Moulton has admitted to using marijuana and supports legalization stating, \"If you're not buying your marijuana from a dealer who sells heroin, who sells opioids, it's much less likely to be a gateway drug,\" he said. \"The problem is now that it operates in the shadows. There's no control whatsoever. Someone goes and buys an edible, for example, there's no regulation about what's in that. It's like moonshine under Prohibition.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bostonmagazine.com/news/blog/2016/09/19/seth-moulton-smoked-pot-legalization/ |work=Boston Magazine |date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Foreign policy====\nMoulton stated his opposition to sending U.S. troops back to Iraq in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.necn.com/news/politics/Seth-Moultons-Bid-to-Unseat-US-Congressman-John-Tierney-271928791.html |title=Seth Moulton's Bid to Unseat US Congressman John Tierney| publisher=New England Cable News |date= August 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Social issues====\nMoulton supports same-sex marriage and abortion rights.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Snow|first1=Justin|title=Democrat Seth Moulton rejects support from same-sex marriage opponents|url=http://www.metroweekly.com/2014/10/democrat-seth-moulton-rejects-support-from-same-sex-marriage-opponents/|accessdate=6 April 2016|publisher=Metro Weekly|date=October 30, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Zengerle|first1=Jason|title=This Massachusetts Race Will Restore Your Faith in Our Democracy|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/120109/tisei-moulton-race-mass-rare-choice-two-great-candidates|accessdate=6 April 2016|publisher=New Republic|date=November 4, 2014}}</ref> He supports increased gun control.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schoenberg|first1=Shira|title=Sen. Elizabeth Warren, Rep. Seth Moulton voice support for President Obama's gun laws|url=http://www.masslive.com/politics/index.ssf/2016/01/sen_elizabeth_warren_rep_seth.html|accessdate=6 April 2016|publisher=Mass Live|date=January 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Transportation policy====\nMoulton is a supporter of implementing high speed rail lines in Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite news|title=Look to Texas Model for Boston rail link|url=http://www.capitalnewyork.com/article/massachusetts/2015/10/8579572/moulton-look-texas-model-boston-rail-link|publisher=Capital New York|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Riding the rails with Moulton |url=http://www.salemnews.com/news/local_news/riding-the-rails-with-moulton/article_5b2ed628-392e-5021-9156-dd3bcc355e02.html|publisher=Salem News|date=March 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Economic policy====\nIn March 2016, with regard to the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]], Moulton said he needed to further analyze the proposal.<ref name=rise/>\n\n====Energy policy====\nMoulton supports the expansion of nuclear energy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wade |first=Christian M. |url=http://www.eagletribune.com/news/pilgrim-s-closure-revives-nuclear-energy-debate/article_c30f2e3f-30fb-5343-8145-66af9d51949d.html |title=Pilgrim's closure revives nuclear energy debate |work=[[The Eagle-Tribune]] |date=2015-10-29 |accessdate=2016-03-24 }}</ref>\n\n====Views on Donald Trump====\nIn an interview with ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' in March 2016, Moulton compared the rise of the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016|Republican presidential front runner]], [[Donald Trump]] with [[Adolf Hitler's rise to power]] in the 1930s. Moulton said that voters should read the history on how the German people elected Hitler in the early 20th century, to understand how an educated society \"can elect a demagogue.\"<ref name=rise>{{cite news |last=Andersen |first=Travis |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2016/03/23/congressman-seth-moulton-compares-rise-donald-trump-election-hitler/5nbZpv2d4B25N2A3hgOldP/story.html |title=Moulton compares Trump\u2019s rise to election of Hitler in 1930s |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=2016-03-24 |accessdate=2016-03-24 }}</ref>\n\n====Gun policy====\nOn June 15, 2016, Moulton appeared on the cover of the ''[[New York Daily News]]'' with the statement 'No Civilian Should Own This Gun' in reference to [[semi-automatic firearm|semi-automatic]] [[assault weapons]]. The cover pictures Moulton from his military service during a deployment to [[Iraq]], carrying an issued [[M4 carbine]].<ref>{{cite news|title=No Civilian Should Own This Weapon|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/nydn-front-pages-2016-gallery-1.2482879?pmSlide=1.2674384|accessdate=17 June 2016|agency=New York Daily News|date=15 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nMoulton penned an opinion piece promoting gun control, including the statement: \"There\u2019s simply no reason for a civilian to own a military-style assault weapon. It\u2019s no different than why we outlaw civilian ownership of rockets and landmines.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Moulton|first1=Seth|title=Civilians have no reason for owning assault weapons, but Congress lacks the courage to stop them: Congressman and Iraq War vet|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/civilians-no-reason-owning-assault-weapons-article-1.2674107|accessdate=17 June 2016|publisher=New York Daily News|date=14 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Electoral history====\n{| class